postcontent:
YOU CAN BUY THIS HERE>Thunder Beast Arms Coporation MODEL 30BA SUPPRESSOR

Brake-attach .30 caliber suppressor

The model 30BA is the brake-attached version of our flagship long-range precision rifle suppressor. It offers best-in-class sound suppression levels in a very light weight format, and is built with accuracy as its first priority. The 30BA is designed to mount over our muzzle brake. It is particularly suited to applications where the rifle will be shot suppressed and unsuppressed, and a brake is desired when shooting without the suppressor.

We developed the 30BA and 338BA to meet the requirement that some customers have for a suppressor that mounts over a muzzle device. We haven't found a "quick mount" on the market that meets our accuracy and repeatability requirements, so we developed the BA series to mount over our brake and provide the same repeatability as our direct thread attach suppressors, like the 30P-1. The 30BA features a conical shoulder for rock solid POI repeatability and to make sure it never comes loose.

The 30BA was designed around .308 for maximum flexibility and is rated up to .300 Winchester Magnum, but it's the ideal suppressor for the most competitive mid-sized cartridges for long-range shooting such as .243 Winchester .260 Remington, 6.5 Creedmoor, 6.5x47 Lapua, 6.5-284 Norma, and 7mm Remington Magnum & WSM.

The 30BA uses the baffle stack of the 30P-1, which has racked up impressive results at long-range field shooting events in the Rocky Mountain region, including the Blue Steel Ranch Steel Safari and the NRA Whittington Center Sporting Rifle Match. Many long-range shooters prefer shooting suppressed because the muzzle blast and concussion is eliminated, while the recoil impulse is reduced and smoothed out over time. The net result is that the rifle is easier to shoot and it's easier to make hits. Communication with your spotter is easier because the need for hearing protection is reduced.

The 30BA is constructed of titanium with a fully-welded baffle core. This material and construction provides a great strength to weight ratio. It can take whatever your precision rifle can dish out.

The 30BA brake will accept the 338BA suppressor, so with a .30 caliber brake on your .308 and a .338 brake on your .338 Lapua Magnum, you can use a single 338BA suppressor on both. The 30BA suppressor will not fit on a 338BA brake.

The 30BA is ideal for: long-range practical competition shooters; varminters; predator hunters; precision tactical shooters.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Remington Model 591M  5MM Magnum
postcontent:
Remington 591 M, 5MM rifle

The 5 mm Remington Rimfire Magnum is a bottlenecked rimfire cartridge introduced by Remington Arms Company in 1969. Remington chambered it in a pair of bolt-action rifles, the Model 591 and Model 592, but the round never became very popular, and the rifles were discontinued in 1973. The ammo is currently being produced by Centurion/Aguila in two versions. About 52,000 rifles were sold during its brief production run. As of 2008, Aguila, a Mexican ammunition company, is producing 5mm Remington Rimfire Magnum ammunition, with two 30gr. bullet designs, at 2300fps and 2400fps, with plans for more bullet selections in the near future.

The 5 mm Mag offers higher velocity than the .22 WMR and more energy than either the .22 WMR or the later .17 HMR.[2] It offers improved performance on small-game and for varmint hunting, along with excellent accuracy.

postcontent: This is a VERY rare 1942 6 groove Smith Corona 1903a3. This is the 1,126th Smith Corona to roll off the assembly line. About as early as you could ever hope to find! Rare with original 6 groove barrel in which they only made approx 4000 of. Here's this bonus, this barrel gauges less than 1 on the ME gauge! A very fine rifle with crisp clean stamp on receiver. No import marks. Has a pristine Remington stock and the historians at the CMP forums have verified that a Remington stock is correct for this rifle. This beauty has been through the Rock Island Armory and has a stunning Parkerized finish. Cross cannons and FJA cartouche's are present but worn as they were right where your thumb hits when handling the rifle. The stock has NOT been refinished and does NOT have on any poly or clear varnish. That is just gorgeous patina. Rifle comes with matching 1942 un cut un molested bayonet and original scabbard. I see a Remington safety selector, dis connector and a couple of the barrel bands. It would take you years to best this Smith Corona. I value it right at $1250.00 with bayonet, 950.00 without. Have seen a comparable 6 groove come through the CMP auction at 2,800.00. I am in Northern Illinois

title: For Sale:  Sears Mod 54
postcontent:
This is an older Sears Model 54 lever action chambered in 30-30 Winchester.
Basically, Winchester made the Model 54 under contract for Sears, so the action is a direct copy of the Winchester model 94. The difference being cheaper wood and quicker manufacturing process; also the markings on the rifle only say Sears.

Unlike the Winchester 94, this rifle is not a collector's item. These rifles were meant to be inexpensive so that they could be used and abused without fear of losing much value. 
Likewise, this rifle shows some pretty heave patina and cosmetic wear. Some of the bluing is chipped in places. 
The action is in good condition and the rifling is fine. 
This would make an excellent saddle or truck gun. Having the reliability and power of a 30-30 without the investment and intrinsic value of a real mod 94. 

Looking to get $200 for this rifle which is fair when compared to the 94's. I will also entertain offers.
I am an FFL, so you will have to pass a background check.

title: For Sale:  Sears Mod 54
postcontent:
This is an older Sears Model 54 lever action chambered in 30-30 Winchester.
Basically, Winchester made the Model 54 under contract for Sears, so the action is a direct copy of the Winchester model 94. The difference being cheaper wood and quicker manufacturing process; also the markings on the rifle only say Sears.

Unlike the Winchester 94, this rifle is not a collector's item. These rifles were meant to be inexpensive so that they could be used and abused without fear of losing much value.
Likewise, this rifle shows some pretty heave patina and cosmetic wear. Some of the bluing is chipped in places.
The action is in good condition and the rifling is fine.
This would make an excellent saddle or truck gun. Having the reliability and power of a 30-30 without the investment and intrinsic value of a real mod 94.

Looking to get $200 for this rifle which is fair when compared to the 94's. I will also entertain offers.
I am an FFL, so you will have to pass a background check (the price for which is included).
